Foot & mouth disease - UK (48) 20010522.0986
[1
Date: 23 May 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: BBC Online, 23 May 2001 [edited
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/uk/scotland/newsid_1347000/1347292.stm>

Scottish farmers have been urged to continue checking for signs of foot and
mouth disease (FMD) among their herds and flocks after new cases were
confirmed in the Borders and Dumfriesshire. The outbreak at Bridge End Farm
at Eastriggs near Annan is the first in Dumfries and Galloway for 10 days.
All 135 cattle will be slaughtered and burned on site. It follows
confirmation of a case near Duns in the Scottish Borders, which was the
first case in that region for 4 weeks.
John Kinnaird, deputy president of the National Farmers' Union of Scotland
(NFUS), said "every precaution possible" was needed to stamp the disease
out. Every vehicle, person, and animal is a potential carrier, he said. The
total number of cases in Scotland now stands at 185, with all but 10 in the
south west.
An emergency coordination group has been set up to make plans for tackling
the latest Borders FMD outbreak. The case was confirmed on Tuesday at
Cothill Farm, near Duns in Berwickshire, a month after the last previous
case in the area. The most recent case near Duns was confirmed at
Rulesmains on 25 April. A spokesman for Borders Council said it was hoped
that arable land around the infected farm would act as a natural firebreak
against any further spread of the disease. Some 800 sheep and 1500 lambs
are to be slaughtered at various locations in the Greenlaw area, all of
which are premises operated by the same farmer. Sheep on 2 neighboring
farms will also be culled, but there will not be an automatic cull in a 3
km zone.
Military personnel will not be involved, but that decision could come under
review if there are further cases. The council said [that, because of
fears expressed elsewhere over public health, the animals are to be taken
for rendering in sealed vehicles.
More than half of all farms in Dumfries and Galloway are believed to have
been affected by a mass cull undertaken in an effort to get rid of the
disease. The new cases follow the discovery of a cluster of 18 cases at
Settle in North Yorkshire. Movement restrictions have been tightened in
Yorkshire amid fears that sheep harboring the disease are infecting cattle
that have been released for pasture.
