[2
Date: 23 May 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhua News Agency via COMTEX, 23 May 2001 [edited

Farm disease cluster sparks alert in north England
-------------------------------------
On Wednesday, the British government decided to sent extra vets and troops
to tackle an outbreak of foot and mouth disease (FMD) in North Yorkshire.
The area around Settle in northern England has seen 17 confirmed FMD cases
since 10 May, the most recent on Tuesday at a farm in Kirby Mallam.
An extra 25 vets were being drafted in, and more troops were being sent to
Settle to oversee the culling operation. Officials now believe the disease
has been in animals in north Yorkshire for 3 weeks. The Ministry of
Agriculture has said the cluster was a "localized" outbreak, not connected
to the widespread movement of infected animals. The ministry admitted the
outbreak was only identified once it began appearing in cattle, and could
have been present in sheep for some weeks. The government has reimposed
movement restrictions on livestock in the Settle and Clitheroe areas, while
investigators attempt to trace the source of the latest cluster. A ministry
spokesman said: "We believe the movements of animals and perhaps people are
partly behind this latest outbreak."
There have been 1628 reported cases of FMD in the UK, resulting in the
slaughter of millions of animals since the first cases were confirmed on
February 20.
